      "date": "2011-11-08 08:36:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 5.6/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/dcd228a8-09e3-11e1-b0d9-52540025f9af).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "d114dc82d9b5f0ef596fa1c3c7c856a0c0f99240",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-08 09:06:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "4449a3c170186f75d1c66793410a86e009120e65",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-07 20:31:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(2 inline comments)\n\nIt is great that this is being added, but it should not be defaulting to an incompatible mode that breaks LST in environments that do not have the same Lustre version everywhere.\n\nInstead, this should default to the old/compatible mode initially, and only if LST_VERSION=1 is set everywhere should it use the new version.  Then, add in a check for a future version of Lustre (e.g. 2.6.50 or so) that will print a #warning and change the default version to the new one:\n\n#if LUSTRE_VERSION_CODE >= OBD_OCD_VERSION(2,6,50,0)\n#warning \"changing LST protocol to use bytes instead of pages, see LU-521\"\n#define LST_PROTO_VERSION LST_PROTO_VERSION_1\n#else\n/* use the old compatible version for now */\n#define LST_PROTO_VERSION LST_PROTO_VERSION_0\n#endif\n\nThis is dependent on whether LST itself detect that the new protocol version is in use or not, otherwise it doesn't really help.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "7a0c84b2a2b1987e7d34b73c91e7a91881d985d0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-22 19:00:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nLiang, about the LST_VERSION and \"session version number\" design. Personally I think it's too complex.\n\nThe original design decision on LST version compatibility was that LST should not handle different versions. Instead, all LST test nodes are supposed to run a same version. If during a rolling upgrade, some nodes have older LST version, then the user should simply upgrade them all to a same LST version. This is easy because:\n1. Unlike Lustre, LST is not a long running service, so nothing gets interrupted.\n2. Test nodes can be upgraded by simply copying a new LST kernel module, without changing anything else.\n\nSo I'd suggest to simply increase SRPC_MSG_VERSION, then all old test nodes will get an EPROTO when the console tries to add them to the session. Of course, console should give a meaningful error message like \"please upgrade LST to version X on these nodes......\".\n\nIn short, it's very easy to upgrade all test nodes to a same LST version (without upgrading Lustre), it doesn't interrupt any service, and it doesn't affect Lustre in any way as LST is completely independent. So all we need to do is increase SRPC_MSG_VERSION and complain about it loudly upon old nodes.\n\nI believed the simplicity of upgrading LST everywhere didn't justify the complexity of version compatibility in LST. Unless my assumption is wrong, I'd like to keep the version code simple - just grouch about it!",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "6d3f90efc9f41d95be969053cfe5f2951a74e18c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-23 02:34:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nIsaac, thanks for looking into it. I think if we don't have version compatibility code in LST, each time we change/add protocol to the latest LST, we have to backport the same feature to old version for each customer, that will make a lot of overhead. i.e: Assume we land this patch to 2.3 and user have nodes running 1.8.7, then we have to port it to 1.8.7 and ask user to upgrade, otherwise their 2.3 nodes can't talk with 1.8.7 which is not very nice.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "f9672d226826f79ecd7f8af16457b51b9c169b95",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-23 06:30:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nI don't think a backport is necessary.\n\nLST is self contained. In the case you described above, a recompilation of LST should suffice:\n1. cp -a 2.3/lnet/selftest/ 1.8.7/lnet/selftest/\n2. rebuild lnet_selftest.ko for 1.8.7\n3. copy lnet_selftest.ko to all 1.8.7 nodes.\n\nThis should be documented somewhere, maybe in lnet/selftest/README. There might be some minor problems like cfs_list_entry is probably list_entry in 1.8.7 - all  can be easily worked around with a simple wrapper header.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "a7208f29108717c69c1150b3b35d54fa27ca8698",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-23 06:41:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nit's not going to work by copy source code and rebuild because we have renamed tons of libcfs APIs for 2.x, selftest source depends on these APIs, also we have moved workitem from selftest to libcfs in 2.x, so we can't build selftest with file copies. If we have a patch for 2.x selftest, we can't directly apply it to 1.8.x because all kinds of conflicts.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "c1739ec9c584aba7adefd6bb42465f306cc217ff",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-01-10 19:57:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nYou're right. We need the version stuff. Please look at my latest comment on LU-521.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "73639ffe9b7f3c465281513a8448983a7d9b8b45",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-01-19 15:49:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: (2 inline comments)\n\nI've changed default version to VESRION_0 so we wouldn't see any warning even there are some old version nodes in the cluster.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
